## Lesson 36-1: Introduction (rc/36-1.tsx)

### After the stem identification breakdown:
{{+Add a brief note: "Unlike other RC question types, Paragraph Function stems are relatively uniform in phrasing — they almost always ask directly about the 'function,' 'purpose,' or what a paragraph 'does.' This means stem identification is straightforward for this type."+}}

### After the five-item function list:
{{+Add a "Function Hierarchy" callout: "This module is the middle step in a three-level analytical skill: Phrase Function (Module 35) asks why a specific detail is there. Paragraph Function (this module) asks why an entire paragraph is there. Passage Function (Module 37) asks why the author wrote the entire text. The same core question — 'what is this doing here?' — applies at every level."+}}

### After the Overarching Takeaway:
{{+Add a "Common Trap" callout: "The most frequent wrong answer on Paragraph Function questions accurately summarizes what the paragraph says rather than describing its role. Always check: does this answer choice describe the paragraph's content, or its job in the argument?"+}}

